fields.name: Fiddle-Leaf Fig Tree
fields.benefits: The broad, violin-shaped leaves make it a highly efficient air purifying plant
fields.description: This shrub boasts a long, elegant stem and branches with broad, leathery leaves. For placement, Schrader suggests “under a skylight or next to a window.” In other words, it needs as much sun as possible. Schrader suggests pruning the top branches when it grows above the window frame.
fields.care: Water once a week, or more if it’s winter and the air in your home is dry.

fields.name: Split-Leaf Philodendron
fields.description: Favored by Henri Matisse, this plant has a distinctive leaf that looks as though it’s been gently cut into by a careful hand. Schrader says you can cut off the top—as long as it has air roots attached—and replant it, meaning if you buy one of these, you could easily have more, if you’d like.

fields.name: Meyer Lemon Tree
fields.description: This tree bears its namesake Meyer lemons, believed to be a hybrid of lemons and mandarin oranges with a subtler, sweeter flavor than lemons. But these trees don’t stop at fruits: “When they bloom you have this beautiful fragrance of citrus flowers,” says Schrader. Meyer lemon trees do well indoors as long as they have lots of sun.

fields.name: Kentia Palm
fields.description: The fronds of this plant spring to great heights from the soil, then lean forward, quietly shading the ground beneath. “It looks great in a big urn,” says Schrader, noting that it should be given lots of space, as it can grow up to 10 feet with a broad reach.
fields.care: Requires medium to bright light; water weekly.

fields.name: Castiron Plant
fields.benefits: Clean Air. Another advantage to the cast iron plant is its ability to improve air quality. An extensive study by NASA proved that indoor plants can absorb harmful chemicals such as benzene and formaldehyde found in office complexes and homes.
fields.description: Schrader says this plant is “mostly for foliage,” meaning if you’re looking to add a lush, dark green plant to your space, this one is for you. It does well in medium to low light and is tolerant of neglect, so it’s fine if you forget to water it once in a while
fields.care: Water once a week or every ten days.

fields.name: Amazon Lily
fields.benefits: They make a fantastic container plant, with its dark green leaves and shade loving.
fields.description: Another dark green plant, but this one features large, white flowers that bloom throughout winter and early spring. “Even when it’s not blooming, it’s nice to look at,” Schrader says. It thrives in medium light; allow soil to dry between watering.
fields.care: The leaves will wilt when it needs water, but once a week should suffice.

fields.name: Snake Plant
fields.description: With sword-shaped leaves winding gently from the soil like charmed snakes from a basket, this indoor house plant strikes a lovely balance between order and chaos.
fields.care: Place anywhere you’d like and let the soil dry completely between watering. Check the soil every week, but it’s fine to skip a few.

fields.name: African Spear Plant
fields.benefits: Known for both looking good and improving air quality.
fields.description: Indeed, this plant’s conical leaves conjure images of spires, obelisks, and skyscrapers.
fields.care: Place in any light you choose; water every few weeks.
